               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "However, we now know that the universe is not composed solely of what we see. We also know that there are extremely small forms of matter and energy that we cannot see (<htcite0>). This fact leads us to an initial reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b2d28a2f-db19-4ca3-a09a-d50b6db5933b",
                     "text": "History Tracers Atlas",
                     "page": "Todo junto",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Is it a matter of size?</b><br /><br />So far, we have applied the Babylonian Diagonal Triple (Pythagorean Theorem) to large squares.<br /><br />Would it be possible to use the same logic for smaller squares?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_limits",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Limits of the Theorem\n\nWhen we first worked with limits in nature, we learned that this idea relates to the values we can achieve in a sequence (<htcite0>). However, in that text, we dealt with large values, such as the squares in **Graph 1**. Now, we need to delve a little deeper into that understanding.\n\n#### Internal Limits\n\nIn another text by History Tracers, we learned that a wide rectangle can be divided into smaller parts. By making these divisions, we go from a rectangle of size 1 to 10 smaller rectangles (**Graph 2**), which we later called tenths (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Natural limits",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
