=\"3\" /> <rect x=\"2\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"43\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>  <rect x=\"84\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>  <rect x=\"125\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/>  <rect x=\"166\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"207\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"248\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"289\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"330\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/> <rect x=\"370\" y=\"2\" width=\"40\" height=\"95\" fill=\"lightblue\" stroke-width=\"1\"/></svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Representation of 10 rectangles along a path showing decimal numbers.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Just as we divided one unit into ten smaller parts, we also learned to divide each of those ten parts into another ten, creating hundredths (<htcite0>). And we can continue making these divisions successively.\n\n#### Reductions in the Theorem\n\nWhat was done with the rectangles in the previous texts can also be done with the squares in **Graph 1** or with any other shape.\n\nSince the Babylonian Diagonal Triple (Pythagorean Theorem) has no limitations regarding the size of the shapes, it remains valid in any scenario.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cade1d55-e344-4f80-b5af-7e66d80112f5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Naming",
                     "date_time": {
